<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Bond Disability and Development group (DDG)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#4f81bd; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; clear:both; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt"><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:15pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Written evidence submitted by </span><br /><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Bond Disability and Development group (DDG)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:15pt"><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:26pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:4pt"><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:26pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Executive Summary</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is a critical moment for disability inclusion in development. The post-2015 process offers the opportunity to build a shared vision of development based on the principle that no intervention should be judged successful if it does not include and empower disabled women, men, girls and boys of all ages and ethnicities – and to make a reality of that vision by ensuring that disability is explicitly included as a core issue within the post-2015 global development framework.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We congratulate the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> government for playing a crucial role in getting disability on the post-2015 agenda, and we call on DFID to seize the moment, and to lead the way in disability inclusion. As a major </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">actor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in global development, DFID has the responsibility and the potential to take a leadership role in this area</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK INGOs represented by DDG are united in our vision of what needs to be done, drawing on a broad range of experience and evidence of what works, and making specific recommendations for action to achieve disability inclusion in all aspects of DFID’s work.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We call on DFID to make a public, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">high level commitment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to include disabled people equitably in its work. In order to fulfill this commitment, we recommend the following action:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Build disability in to DFID’s strategic frameworks</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Appoint a Disability Champion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Develop planning and accountability systems which promote disability inclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Invest in learning and evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:14pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Promote the voice and participation of disabled people</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="color:#548dd4; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 6pt 21.3pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">B</span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">ond</span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold"> Disability and Development Group</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Bond Disability and Development Group (DDG) brings together UK-based mainstream and disability-specific </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to ensure that disabled people’s</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> concerns are addressed at the highest level. The member </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of DDG represent a large body of experience based on direct work with disabled people and the disability movement in developing countries, as well as advocacy and policy engagement with service providers and policymakers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DDG is therefore able to draw on a broad and deep understanding of the barriers faced by disabled people of all ages, the links between disability and poverty, and the importance of including disability issues within the development process. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This submission represents a synthesis of the key messages emerging from DDG member </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> individual submissions to the IDSC, and we indicate where these can be referenced for greater detail on specific issues.  </span></p><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 6pt 21.3pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Disability is a core development issue</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is a growing understanding that development interventions will fail to reach the poorest unless disability issues and disabled people are included: Disability is increasingly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recognised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as a core development issue, not just because disabled people make up 15% of all populations, but because of the close links between disability, poverty, and exclusion (WHO/World Bank 2011, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Mitra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> et al 2012), and evidence that the exclusion of disabled people from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">labour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> markets has a negative impact on economies in poorer countries (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Buckup</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, ILO Report 2009).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disability needs to be understood primarily as a social and human rights issue: It is the combination of discrimination with social and environmental barriers which excludes and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">marginalises</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> disabled people, and which traps a disproportionate number in poverty (WHO/World Bank 2011). </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disabled people do not represent a homogenous group – disability is one of many intersecting factors (including age, gender, ethnicity etc.)  which combine to intensify social inequalities and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">marginalisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. And disability also interacts with other issues to influence development outcomes; for example, conflict and violence can create disability, while disability increases vulnerability in such contexts (HI submission).</span><span style="color:#943634; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disability inclusion is about improving the quality rather than the quantity of UK aid and development </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: An investment in disability inclusion represents value for money. For disability inclusion to be effective, political commitment needs to be supported with an investment of resources: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> spent £9.5m on disability in 2012/13 and has dedicated a further £10.6m for 2013/14. Mainstreaming disability from the start of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> represents the best value for money e.g. by incorporating inclusive design in new infrastructure, and USAID has found that most modifications to ensure the inclusion of disabled people in mainstream projects can often be implemented without additional costs (USAID website 1.12.13.). </span></p><h2 style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">A critical moment for disability inclusion</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disability is finally emerging as a core issue within the international development debate, as reflected in the recent High Level Panel and Secretary General’s reports on the post-2015 Development Framework. These documents call for a transformative shift which ‘leaves no one behind’, they highlight the importance of disaggregating indicators to support this, and state that ‘no target should be considered met unless met for all social groups, including people with disabilities’.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, these gains will not be secured until the final framework is agreed - continued pressure and vigilance will be needed to ensure that disability inclusion remains explicit and does not get lost or subsumed into general statements about ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">marginalised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> groups’ at the last moment. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">DFID’s approach to date</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The UK government has a duty in international law, under Article 32 of the UNCRPD, to ensure that all international cooperation including development </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, is ‘inclusive of and accessible to persons with disabilities.’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID has a good track record on its analysis of the importance of disability inclusion and was one of the first bilateral agencies to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recognise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the central importance of disability to development in its 2000 paper on Disability, Poverty and Development. This was followed in 2007 with the How to Note on Working on Disability in Country </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and various guidance notes on disability related issues. However this analysis and guidance is not well known within DFID, and has not translated into systematic inclusion practice across all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is currently no DFID policy or strategy on disability, and there is no obligation for DFID </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to demonstrate or monitor the inclusion of disabled people in their work, e.g. through the disaggregation of data by disability. As a result we do not even know whether disabled people benefit equitably from DFID’s aid and development </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. However, DDG members’ experience and evidence of the barriers which exclude disabled people from all areas of life would suggest that, without targeted action to ensure inclusion, it is most probable that disabled people are not currently benefitting equitably within mainstream </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> know that disability is not adequately reflected within strategic documents in other areas, such as the Strategic Vision for Women and Girls, and DFID’s work also lacks a focus on different needs across the life course and this has implications for disabled people’s inclusion, given the links between disability and ageing. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID and UK parliamentarians have played a crucially important role in getting disability on the post-2015 agenda, and key individuals within DFID are currently championing disability inclusion, leading to positive initiatives such as the recent announcement that all schools built with DFID funding will be required to be physically accessible, including WASH services, and the commitment to work with partners globally to improve data and evidence. However, the institutional structures and systems are not in place to ensure that this current interest is embedded at all levels or sustained as individuals move on. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">UK INGOs’ experience </span></h2><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Individual submissions are being made from DDG members and other allied UK INGOs, and these represent a rich source of evidence and experience relating to different aspects of disability inclusion in development, as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">summarised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> below. Each of these submissions makes recommendations relating to specific issues, and all have contributed to, and endorse, the overarching recommendations in this paper. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">HelpAge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> International,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Age International</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Alzheimer’s Disease International</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emphasise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the need for a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">lifecycle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> approach to disability inclusion, and for specific attention to the barriers facing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">older disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in a context where global populations are ageing (Ageing in the 21</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Century) and the number of older people with care needs is set to treble by 2050, with an increasing proportion in poorer countries (World Alzheimer Report 2013).</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Submissions from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Plan UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">AbleChildAfrica</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emphasise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the importance of tackling the discrimination faced by disabled</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and developing initiatives which address their developmental needs and promote their inclusion in mainstream service provision in order to avoid the negative cycle of exclusion and poverty. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Leonard Cheshire Disability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (LCD)’s experience demonstrates the value of initiatives which make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">young disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> agents of their own change within development </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The value of joined-up, holistic approaches to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">early childhood development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is illustrated by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sense</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, while approaches which tackle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">violence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> against disabled children are demonstrated by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Plan UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  Special attention is needed to achieve the inclusion of children with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> intellectual disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> severe or complex disabilities: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sense International </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">underlines the importance of working with stakeholders to develop specialist knowledge on developing communication, social, mobility and practical skills.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The importance of access to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">education </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which responds to the needs of disabled children is crucial: Submissions from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Plan UK, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">AbleChildAfrica</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, Global Campaign for Education (GCE)/ RESULTS UK, and Handicap International (HI) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provide insights into this challenge, recognizing DFID’s efforts in this area, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">analysing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> why these good intentions are not always translated into good practice on the ground. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="color:#548dd4; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The double and sometimes triple discrimination faced by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">disabled women/ older women and girls</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is evidenced in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">GADN Gender and Disability Working Group’s submission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, which finds that gender focused policies and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> often neglect the disability dimension, thereby further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">marginalising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> disabled women and girls.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">HI and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sightsavers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emphasises</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the importance of access to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">health</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> services including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rehabilitation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which is often perceived as a ‘luxury’ and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">woefully limited despite the transformative impact it can have on the lives of disabled people and their families. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">STOPAIDS </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provides evidence on the specific vulnerability of disabled people, and in particular disabled women and girls, to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">HIV/AIDs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and the barriers they face to accessing information and support. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">WaterAid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> highlights how lack of accessible </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">WASH</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (water, sanitation and hygiene) can impact on disabled people, particularly disabled women and girls for whom accessing WASH facilities can present additional challenges and vulnerability, and provides evidence of effective, low cost approaches to ensuring that disabled people are included in WASH </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ADD International’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> experience of working in alliance with disability rights movements </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emphasises</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the importance of disabled people’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">empowerment and participation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in development processes – not simply as beneficiaries, but as agents of their own development – and of the value of bringing the voice of disabled people into policymaking, governance and accountability processes by identifying and removing the barriers which exclude them. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sense International</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Leprosy Mission England &amp; Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> highlight the value of initiatives which tackle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">social stigma </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in tackling the isolation and exclusion of disabled people, particularly the most excluded (albinism, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">deafblind</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, intellectual disability etc.), including through participation in mainstream </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which builds understanding between disabled and non-disabled people. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Motivation’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> work evidences the importance of adherence to international guidelines on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">assistive devices</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in enabling disabled people to access services (health and education) and to participate in social and economic activities: Without inputs which support mobility and communication, disabled people are unable to benefit equitably from development interventions and remain ‘left behind’.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">importance of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">livelihoods</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to disabled people's empowerment - social as well as economic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">– is reflected in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">CBM’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s submission which highlights the importance of inclusive practice in mainstream credit &amp; savings programmes, as well as inclusive employment policy and practice supported by legal frameworks. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Recent research finds that only 1% of international humanitarian aid is dedicated to disabled or older people, while evidence from the crisis in Syria shows that the barriers faced by disabled and older people often mean that they are effectively excluded from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">humanitarian responses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">HI/HAI)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">HI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recognises</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">steps taken by DFID’s humanitarian team to improve age/disability inclusion (e.g. included in 2011 Humanitarian Policy) but calls for this to be consolidated through more systematic approaches. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The importance and challenges of generating the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">data and evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on which effective </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> must be based is demonstrated through submissions from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">International Centre for Evidence in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Disability (ICED)/ London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine (LSHTM</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">).</span></p><h2 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">What works: Inclusive Approaches</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The collective evidence and recommendations put forward by INGOs working on diverse but related issues highlight the following key approaches to effective disability inclusion: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Strategic approaches to ensure sustainability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: Disability inclusion needs to be built in to the culture and systems of mainstream </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> at all levels. The ‘Development for All’ strategy in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">AusAid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, for example, has been effective in achieving good practice and positive impact for disabled people (Development for All Strategy Mid-Term Review 2012)</span><span style="color:#548dd4; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Twin-track approaches:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Efforts to ensure that mainstream development is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">disability-inclusive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (e.g. education </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that include disabled boys and girls) need to be supported by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">disability-specific</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> inputs (e.g. accessible schools/ outreach with disabled children and families). </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Locate disability within the equity debate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: Disability must be understood in the context of multiple and intersecting factors which contribute to exclusion and disadvantage. We need to ensure that disability is embedded, but not overlooked, within the wider equity discourse.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Participation of disabled people: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Policy and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> development must draw on the lived experience of disabled people and promote their participation as agents of change. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Reasonable accommodation/ Positive Action:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Ensuring accessibility of mainstream </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> e.g. through inclusive design and modifications, assistive inputs, and removal of physical, communication and attitudinal barriers. Breaking negative cycles of exclusion and discrimination by creating opportunities for disabled people to participate in the workforce. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Evidence based programming: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disaggregation of data by disability alongside other factors (gender, age, ethnicity, geographic location); qualitative and quantitative evidence on exclusion/barriers to inclusion; learning from what works; and listening to the voices of disabled people through all these processes.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Access to specialist skills and knowledge:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> staff and other stakeholders need access to advice, peer support and learning, information and resources on inclusive approaches. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations </span></h2><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Seize the moment and reclaim a leading role:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> As one of the world’s largest and most influential development actors, the UK and DFID should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> aim to excel and provide leadership </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on all core humanitarian and development issues – including disability. It must do this by developing and demonstrating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> good practice, within sustainable systems and structures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which adhere to international law and guidelines on disability, ageing, gender, children and other related issues, and make a reality of the ‘leave no one behind’ agenda. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Make a commitment to disability inclusion at the highest level:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> In order to support the explicit inclusion of disability issues in the post-2015 framework, and to ensure that this is not lost at the 11</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> hour, DFID should maintain the momentum by making </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">a public pledge to include disabled people equitably</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in its work. We recommend that this pledge is made during 2014, in order to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">maximise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the potential for influencing the post-2015 framework to be explicitly inclusive of disability. The pledge should be realistic, specific, phased and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">timebound</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (e.g. begin by achieving inclusion in one or more bilateral aid </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or sector by 2016), and supported by the following action to ensure it is achieved:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Build disability in to DFID’s strategic frameworks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:  Develop a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Strategic Vision for Disabled People</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Disability Theory of Change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, drawing on experience from existing approaches to gender within DFID’s work. These instruments should reflect the intersecting nature of diverse factors which contribute to the exclusion of disabled people of all ages, but they must also identify the specific measures needed to ensure disabled people are included. In order to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">maximise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the impact of this strategic vision and TOC, we call for DFID to develop an overarching </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Equity and Inclusion Strategy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which brings together the different factors which impact on equity, such as disability, age, gender etc. This approach to equity and inclusion should be reflected through </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">revisions to DFID’s Business Plan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Appoint a Disability Champion:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The practical application of the above strategic frameworks will have greatest impact if it is driven forward by key individuals. We recommend the appointment of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Disability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Champion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at senior level (this post in USAID is appointed by the president), linked to identified ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">lead’ staff in country offices</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. These posts, which need not be new appointments, will require training, guidance and resources to fulfil their role. In order </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to provide advice on disability inclusion, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Social Development Advisors</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> must have sufficient training and technical background, including knowledge of the disability sector and key </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for referral. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Develop planning and accountability systems which promote disability inclusion:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Specific changes need to be made to the processes for approving and reporting on funding for DFID country </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, humanitarian response, and CSO partners. This should include a requirement to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">disaggregate data</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (by disability, age gender and other factors), and mechanisms to ensure disability is included at the planning stage (e.g. similar to the 2010 Bilateral Aid Review which asked country offices to state how their interventions would impact on women and girls). </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Invest in learning and evidence:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID should exercise political leadership and invest resources in developing work with bilateral/ multilateral </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and CSOs to improve the generation and uptake of: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">disability data</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">qualitative and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">quantitiative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on the barriers to inclusion; and evidence of effective approaches to inclusion. All of these initiatives should be based on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">lived experience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of disabled people, promoting their voice and participation in learning and policy development processes.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">8.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Promote the voice and participation of disabled people:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Initiatives are needed to promote the active participation of disabled stakeholders in planning, implementation and accountability processes at all levels.  DFID should aim to model good practice in this area e.g. through inclusive design, accessible information and systems, and positive action to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">bring more disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of all ages and of different gender into </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DFID's workforce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in delivery and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">decisionmaking</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> roles. We recommend that DFID starts this process by including disabled people in developing the Strategic Vision for Disabled People/ Disability TOC.</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> In this submission </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">‘disabled people’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> refers to disabled people of all ages, ethnicities and locations, and of both genders. The term refl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">ect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> the terminology of the UK disability rights movement, but we recognise that in different contexts ‘people with disabilities’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">is used, while the UNCRPD refe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">rs to ‘persons with disabilities’.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p></body></html>